---
import Canvas from "../layouts/Canvas.astro";
const styles = `
    .check-list { display: flex; flex-direction: column; gap: 8px; counter-reset: chk; }
    .check-item {
      display: grid;
      grid-template-columns: 36px 1fr;
      gap: 12px;
      padding: 12px 16px;
      border: 1px solid var(--border);
      border-radius: var(--radius-md);
      background: var(--card);
    }
    .check-item::before {
      counter-increment: chk;
      content: counter(chk, decimal-leading-zero);
      font-family: var(--font-mono);
      font-size: 11px;
      color: var(--text-muted);
      align-self: center;
    }
    .check-item .check-title { font-weight: 600; font-size: 13.5px; margin-bottom: 2px; }
    .check-item .check-desc { font-size: 12.5px; color: var(--text-muted); }
    .json-block {
      background: var(--card);
      border: 1px solid var(--border);
      border-radius: var(--radius-md);
      padding: 16px 20px;
      font-family: var(--font-mono);
      font-size: 12px;
      line-height: 1.6;
      white-space: pre;
      overflow-x: auto;
      color: var(--text-primary);
    }
  `;
---

<Canvas title="08 · Policy Engine — Sardis Canvas" currentId="policy-engine">
<Fragment slot="head">
  <style is:global set:html={styles}></style>
</Fragment>

<section class="hero">
        <span class="eyebrow">Canvas 08 · Flows</span>
        <h1>Policy Engine</h1>
        <p class="hero-lead">
          The hard part of agent payments isn't access to money — it's controlling authority over money.
          The policy engine is Sardis's answer: natural-language intent → structured rule → enforced on every
          transaction, logged with a reason code, anchored on-chain. This canvas walks the whole pipeline.
        </p>
      </section>

      <section class="section" style="padding-top:0; border-top:0;">
        <div class="callout callout-info">
          <span class="callout-title">TL;DR</span>
          <code>SpendingPolicy.evaluate()</code> in
          <code>packages/sardis-core/src/sardis_v2_core/spending_policy.py</code> runs twelve checks in a fixed
          order; the first failure short-circuits with a reason code. Above it sits a natural-language parser
          (Groq Llama 3.3 70B, regex fallback). Below it sits an approval queue, a decision log, a simulation
          sandbox, and — for mandates that clear the gate — on-chain enforcement via ERC-8183.
        </div>
      </section>

      <!-- Thesis -->
      <section class="section">
        <div class="section-header">
          <div class="eyebrow">Thesis</div>
          <h2>Why "authority" — not "access" — is the problem.</h2>
          <p class="text-muted" style="max-width:760px;">
            Giving an agent a wallet takes ten minutes. Giving an agent a wallet it <em>cannot misuse</em>
            is the actual product. Every design choice in this engine follows from that.
          </p>
        </div>
        <div class="grid grid-2">
          <div class="card">
            <div class="card-title">Access is easy. Revocation is hard.</div>
            <div class="card-description">
              An MPC signer solves "the agent can pay." It does nothing about "the agent decided to pay
              $40K to a phishing address at 3am because a jailbreak prompt told it to." Policy is the layer
              that says no on the agent's behalf, <em>before</em> the signer is even asked.
            </div>
          </div>
          <div class="card">
            <div class="card-title">Authority must be structured, not trusted.</div>
            <div class="card-description">
              Natural language ("$500/day on API credits, openai.com only") is the <em>input</em>, not the
              enforcement. The parser converts intent into a typed <code>SpendingPolicy</code> dataclass with
              hard caps, allowlists, time windows — data structures that can be evaluated in &lt;1ms on every tx.
            </div>
          </div>
          <div class="card">
            <div class="card-title">Fail-closed, with a reason.</div>
            <div class="card-description">
              Every denial returns a machine-readable reason code
              (<code>per_transaction_limit</code>, <code>merchant_denied</code>, <code>goal_drift_exceeded</code>).
              No silent rejects, no vague "declined." Agents, operators, and regulators see the same root cause.
            </div>
          </div>
          <div class="card">
            <div class="card-title">Evidence beats logs.</div>
            <div class="card-description">
              Every allow and every deny writes a row to the decision log. Batches are Merkle-rooted and
              anchored by <code>SardisLedgerAnchor.sol</code>. "Trust our logs" is not a defense; a Merkle
              proof is.
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </section>

      <!-- NL → structured -->
      <section class="section">
        <div class="section-header">
          <div class="eyebrow">Pipeline</div>
          <h2>Natural language → structured policy.</h2>
          <p class="text-muted" style="max-width:760px;">
            Operators type English. Agents hit a typed dataclass. The parser bridges the two and is
            implemented twice — once as an LLM call, once as a regex fallback — so the stack never hard-fails
            on a missing API key.
          </p>
        </div>

        <div class="grid grid-2">
          <div class="card">
            <div class="card-title">Input (what the operator types)</div>
            <pre><code>Spend up to $500/day on API credits,
only to api.openai.com and api.anthropic.com.
Require human approval above $200.
Block gambling (MCC 7995) and adult (MCC 5967).</code></pre>
          </div>
          <div class="card">
            <div class="card-title">Output (what the engine sees)</div>
            <div class="json-block">SpendingPolicy(
  agent_id = "agent_123",
  trust_level = TrustLevel.MEDIUM,
  limit_per_tx = Decimal("200"),
  daily_limit = TimeWindowLimit(
    limit = Decimal("500"),
    window = "daily",
    scope = SpendingScope.COMPUTE,
  ),
  merchant_rules = [
    MerchantRule(merchant_id="api.openai.com",   allowed=True),
    MerchantRule(merchant_id="api.anthropic.com", allowed=True),
  ],
  blocked_merchant_categories = ["gambling", "adult"],
  approval_threshold = Decimal("200"),
)</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="grid grid-2 mt-24">
          <div class="card">
            <div class="card-title">Primary: Groq Llama 3.3 70B</div>
            <div class="card-description">
              <code>NLPolicyParser</code> in <code>nl_policy_parser.py</code>. Uses
              <code>llama-3.3-70b-versatile</code> via the Groq OpenAI-compatible endpoint
              (<code>https://api.groq.com/openai/v1</code>). ~200ms typical; open-source model so there's no
              proprietary lock-in on the parsing layer itself. Falls through to OpenAI if
              <code>GROQ_API_KEY</code> is unset and <code>OPENAI_API_KEY</code> is present.
            </div>
          </div>
          <div class="card">
            <div class="card-title">Fallback: regex parser</div>
            <div class="card-description">
              <code>RegexPolicyParser</code> in the same file. Pattern-matches common phrasings
              ("$X/day", "only to Y", "block Z") so policy creation still works in airgapped / sandbox
              environments with no LLM key. Less expressive, but never hallucinates a field. Invariants live
              in <code>ImmutableParserHardLimits</code> — hard ceilings the LLM can't raise.
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </section>

      <!-- Dimensions -->
      <section class="section">
        <div class="section-header">
          <div class="eyebrow">Dimensions</div>
          <h2>What a policy can actually control.</h2>
          <p class="text-muted" style="max-width:760px;">
            Each field on <code>SpendingPolicy</code> is a lever. Most deployments only touch three or four;
            the rest exist for edge cases that show up at scale.
          </p>
        </div>
        <table class="data">
          <thead>
            <tr><th>Dimension</th><th>Field on SpendingPolicy</th><th>What it controls</th></tr>
          </thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr><td>Per-transaction cap</td><td><code>limit_per_tx</code></td><td>Max single payment. Category-specific overrides via <code>_get_effective_per_tx_limit()</code>.</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Lifetime cap</td><td><code>limit_total</code> + <code>spent_total</code></td><td>Cumulative ceiling across the policy's lifetime.</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Daily / weekly / monthly</td><td><code>daily_limit</code>, <code>weekly_limit</code>, <code>monthly_limit</code></td><td><code>TimeWindowLimit</code> objects — rolling windows, race-safe reads from <code>policy_store</code>.</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Merchant allow / block</td><td><code>merchant_rules</code></td><td>Per-merchant caps, category matching. Case-insensitive — deliberate, prevents casing-trick bypass.</td></tr>
            <tr><td>MCC blocking</td><td><code>blocked_merchant_categories</code></td><td>4-digit Merchant Category Codes (e.g. 7995 gambling, 5967 adult).</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Scope restriction</td><td><code>allowed_scopes</code></td><td><code>SpendingScope</code> enum: retail, compute, agent_to_agent, etc. <code>ALL</code> is the wildcard.</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Chain / token allowlist</td><td><code>allowed_chains</code>, <code>allowed_tokens</code></td><td>Restrict which rails a policy authorizes (e.g. "Base + USDC only").</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Destination allowlist</td><td><code>allowed_destination_addresses</code> / <code>blocked_destination_addresses</code></td><td>Hard address pins — for treasury sweeps, known suppliers.</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Approval threshold</td><td><code>approval_threshold</code></td><td>Above this amount, route to human queue instead of auto-approving.</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Goal-drift guard</td><td><code>max_drift_score</code></td><td>If the agent has drifted from its stated task (<code>goal_drift_detector.py</code>), deny.</td></tr>
            <tr><td>KYA attestation gate</td><td>(via <code>kya_client</code> arg)</td><td>Require on-chain agent identity attestation before high-value flows.</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Merchant trust</td><td>(via <code>merchant_trust_service</code>)</td><td>First-seen or low-trust merchants get extra scrutiny regardless of other rules.</td></tr>
            <tr><td>Pre-auth hold</td><td><code>require_preauth</code>, <code>max_hold_hours</code></td><td>Force a two-step "authorize then capture" instead of a single settlement.</td></tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </section>

      <!-- Evaluation order -->
      <section class="section">
        <div class="section-header">
          <div class="eyebrow">Evaluation</div>
          <h2>Twelve checks, fixed order, first fail wins.</h2>
          <p class="text-muted" style="max-width:760px;">
            The order in <code>SpendingPolicy.evaluate()</code> is not arbitrary — cheap local checks run
            first, DB and on-chain lookups later. Short-circuiting saves latency on the common "just blatantly
            over the limit" case.
          </p>
        </div>
        <div class="check-list">
          <div class="check-item"><div><div class="check-title">Amount validation</div><div class="check-desc"><code>amount &gt; 0</code> and <code>fee &gt;= 0</code>. Reason codes: <code>amount_must_be_positive</code>, <code>fee_must_be_non_negative</code>.</div></div></div>
          <div class="check-item"><div><div class="check-title">Scope allowed</div><div class="check-desc"><code>scope ∈ allowed_scopes</code> (or <code>ALL</code>). Reason: <code>scope_not_allowed</code>.</div></div></div>
          <div class="check-item"><div><div class="check-title">MCC not blocked</div><div class="check-desc"><code>_check_mcc_policy(mcc_code)</code> — 4-digit category screen.</div></div></div>
          <div class="check-item"><div><div class="check-title">Per-transaction limit</div><div class="check-desc">Effective cap = min(category override, trust-tier cap, global cap). Reason: <code>per_transaction_limit</code>.</div></div></div>
          <div class="check-item"><div><div class="check-title">Lifetime cap</div><div class="check-desc">From <code>policy_store</code> in prod, in-memory in dev. Reason: <code>total_limit_exceeded</code>.</div></div></div>
          <div class="check-item"><div><div class="check-title">Time-window limits</div><div class="check-desc">Daily / weekly / monthly rolling windows. Reasons: <code>daily_limit_exceeded</code>, <code>weekly_limit_exceeded</code>, <code>monthly_limit_exceeded</code>.</div></div></div>
          <div class="check-item"><div><div class="check-title">On-chain balance</div><div class="check-desc">If <code>rpc_client</code> provided — is the wallet actually fundable? Reason: <code>insufficient_balance</code>.</div></div></div>
          <div class="check-item"><div><div class="check-title">Merchant rules</div><div class="check-desc">Allowlist, blocklist, per-merchant caps. Reason: <code>merchant_denied</code>.</div></div></div>
          <div class="check-item"><div><div class="check-title">Goal drift</div><div class="check-desc"><code>drift_score &gt; max_drift_score</code> → deny. Reason: <code>goal_drift_exceeded</code>.</div></div></div>
          <div class="check-item"><div><div class="check-title">Merchant trust</div><div class="check-desc">First-seen or low-trust merchants fail unless the policy explicitly allows unknown destinations.</div></div></div>
          <div class="check-item"><div><div class="check-title">Approval threshold</div><div class="check-desc">If <code>amount ≥ approval_threshold</code>: return <code>(True, "requires_approval")</code> and hand off to approval queue.</div></div></div>
          <div class="check-item"><div><div class="check-title">KYA attestation</div><div class="check-desc">For high-value paths, verify on-chain agent identity via <code>kya_client</code>. No attestation → deny.</div></div></div>
        </div>
      </section>

      <!-- Decision tree -->
      <section class="section">
        <div class="section-header">
          <div class="eyebrow">Decision tree</div>
          <h2>What evaluate() looks like as a flowchart.</h2>
        </div>
        <div class="diagram">
          <pre class="mermaid" is:raw>
flowchart TD
    A[Payment request] --> B{amount > 0 &amp; fee &gt;= 0?}
    B -- no --> D1[deny: amount_must_be_positive]
    B -- yes --> C{scope allowed?}
    C -- no --> D2[deny: scope_not_allowed]
    C -- yes --> D{MCC blocked?}
    D -- yes --> D3[deny: mcc_blocked]
    D -- no --> E{per-tx cap OK?}
    E -- no --> D4[deny: per_transaction_limit]
    E -- yes --> F{lifetime cap OK?}
    F -- no --> D5[deny: total_limit_exceeded]
    F -- yes --> G{time-window OK?}
    G -- no --> D6[deny: daily/weekly/monthly_limit_exceeded]
    G -- yes --> H{balance sufficient?}
    H -- no --> D7[deny: insufficient_balance]
    H -- yes --> I{merchant allowed?}
    I -- no --> D8[deny: merchant_denied]
    I -- yes --> J{drift &lt; max?}
    J -- no --> D9[deny: goal_drift_exceeded]
    J -- yes --> K{amount &ge; approval_threshold?}
    K -- yes --> L[requires_approval → queue]
    K -- no --> M{KYA attested?}
    M -- no --> D10[deny: kya_required]
    M -- yes --> N[ALLOW → orchestrator → signer]
          </pre>
        </div>
      </section>

      <!-- Reason codes -->
      <section class="section">
        <div class="section-header">
          <div class="eyebrow">Reason codes</div>
          <h2>Every denial is explainable.</h2>
          <p class="text-muted" style="max-width:760px;">
            These strings are the contract between engine, operator dashboard, and the decision log. Don't
            invent new ones casually — they're indexed, alerted on, and quoted in incident reports.
          </p>
        </div>
        <table class="data">
          <thead><tr><th>Reason code</th><th>Meaning</th><th>Typical fix</th></tr></thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr><td><code>OK</code></td><td>Allowed.</td><td>—</td></tr>
            <tr><td><code>requires_approval</code></td><td>Allowed if an approver signs off.</td><td>Route to <code>ApprovalService</code>.</td></tr>
            <tr><td><code>amount_must_be_positive</code></td><td>Bad input.</td><td>SDK-level validation should catch first.</td></tr>
            <tr><td><code>fee_must_be_non_negative</code></td><td>Bad input.</td><td>Gas estimator bug — investigate.</td></tr>
            <tr><td><code>scope_not_allowed</code></td><td>Spending category not in allowlist.</td><td>Expand <code>allowed_scopes</code> or re-route request.</td></tr>
            <tr><td><code>mcc_blocked</code></td><td>Merchant category blocked (e.g. gambling).</td><td>Confirm with operator before unblocking.</td></tr>
            <tr><td><code>per_transaction_limit</code></td><td>Single payment above cap.</td><td>Raise <code>limit_per_tx</code> or split payment.</td></tr>
            <tr><td><code>total_limit_exceeded</code></td><td>Lifetime ceiling hit.</td><td>Top up <code>limit_total</code> or rotate policy.</td></tr>
            <tr><td><code>daily_limit_exceeded</code></td><td>Daily window exhausted.</td><td>Wait for reset or raise window.</td></tr>
            <tr><td><code>insufficient_balance</code></td><td>Wallet can't cover.</td><td>Fund wallet or route via CCTP.</td></tr>
            <tr><td><code>merchant_denied</code></td><td>Merchant blocked or not on allowlist.</td><td>Review allowlist.</td></tr>
            <tr><td><code>goal_drift_exceeded</code></td><td>Agent off-task per drift detector.</td><td>Investigate agent — potential jailbreak or goal-hijack.</td></tr>
            <tr><td><code>kya_required</code></td><td>No on-chain agent attestation.</td><td>Run KYA onboarding for the agent.</td></tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </section>

      <!-- Mandates + ERC-8183 -->
      <section class="section">
        <div class="section-header">
          <div class="eyebrow">On-chain enforcement</div>
          <h2>Spending mandates — from a Python object to an EVM guard.</h2>
          <p class="text-muted" style="max-width:760px;">
            A policy is off-chain: Sardis trusts itself. A <em>spending mandate</em> is the same policy
            cryptographically committed — first to Sardis's append-only log via AGIT, then to an on-chain
            guard via ERC-8183. If Sardis is compromised, the chain still enforces the cap.
          </p>
        </div>
        <div class="grid grid-2">
          <div class="card">
            <div class="card-title">Off-chain: AGIT policy chain</div>
            <div class="card-description">
              <code>AgitPolicyEngine</code> in <code>agit_policy_engine.py</code>. Every
              <code>commit_policy()</code> hashes the policy and links it to the prior commit, forming a
              tamper-evident chain. <code>verify_policy_chain(agent_id)</code> proves the current policy
              descends from the original — a policy flip doesn't go unnoticed.
            </div>
          </div>
          <div class="card">
            <div class="card-title">On-chain: ERC-8183 guard</div>
            <div class="card-description">
              <code>ERC8183PolicyGuard</code> in <code>erc8183_policy_guard.py</code>. Before funding or
              settlement, the guard calls <code>evaluate_funding</code> / <code>submit_funding</code> /
              <code>submit_settlement</code> — the solidity-side hooks reject if the on-chain policy record
              doesn't match. Caps currently enforced: 1% fee ceiling, USDC-only, trust hooks disabled
              (post-audit relaxation path).
            </div>
          </div>
          <div class="card">
            <div class="card-title">Why both?</div>
            <div class="card-description">
              Off-chain policy runs on every request — cheap, flexible, covers all rails including fiat.
              On-chain policy is the last line when counterparty trust in Sardis drops to zero (regulator,
              enterprise treasury, dispute). They agree in the common case; they diverge only when Sardis
              itself is the attacker, and the on-chain side wins.
            </div>
          </div>
          <div class="card">
            <div class="card-title">ERC-20 hook surface</div>
            <div class="card-description">
              The guard publishes three evaluation points on-chain:
              <code>evaluate_funding</code> (pre-transfer sanity), <code>submit_funding</code> (commits
              the intent to a job), <code>submit_settlement</code> (finalizes the settlement hash).
              Each raises <code>ERC8183PolicyDenied</code> on mismatch.
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </section>

      <!-- Delegation -->
      <section class="section">
        <div class="section-header">
          <div class="eyebrow">Delegation</div>
          <h2>Parent → child mandate trees.</h2>
          <p class="text-muted" style="max-width:760px;">
            Real agent systems are multi-agent. A team lead agent hires helpers; a workflow fans out to
            sub-tasks. Each child needs spending authority — but strictly less than the parent's, never more.
            That's what <code>mandate_tree.py</code> enforces.
          </p>
        </div>
        <div class="grid grid-2">
          <div class="card">
            <div class="card-title">MandateTreeNode</div>
            <div class="card-description">
              A node holds the mandate (limits, scopes, expiry) plus a list of children. <code>is_leaf()</code>
              and <code>total_delegated()</code> let callers reason about the tree without walking it manually.
            </div>
          </div>
          <div class="card">
            <div class="card-title">MandateTreeValidator.validate_delegation()</div>
            <div class="card-description">
              Invariants: child <code>limit_per_tx</code> ≤ parent's; child <code>total_delegated ≤ parent.limit_total</code>;
              child expiry ≤ parent expiry; scope must be a subset. Violation → deny. This is the "can't
              issue more authority than you have" rule, enforced structurally.
            </div>
          </div>
          <div class="card">
            <div class="card-title">build_mandate_tree()</div>
            <div class="card-description">
              Reconstructs the full tree from the DB for audit and visualization. The dashboard's mandate
              view reads from this; investigators reading a decision log can reconstruct the delegation
              chain that authorized a specific payment.
            </div>
          </div>
          <div class="card">
            <div class="card-title">Revocation cascades</div>
            <div class="card-description">
              Revoking a parent mandate invalidates every descendant at the next evaluation. No "zombie
              sub-agents kept spending after the main agent was killed" story. This matters for incident
              response.
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </section>

      <!-- Approvals -->
      <section class="section">
        <div class="section-header">
          <div class="eyebrow">Approvals</div>
          <h2>When policy says "maybe."</h2>
          <p class="text-muted" style="max-width:760px;">
            A request above <code>approval_threshold</code> isn't denied — it's queued. A human operator,
            a second agent, or a group vote can release it. <code>ApprovalService</code> in
            <code>approval_service.py</code> owns the lifecycle.
          </p>
        </div>
        <table class="data">
          <thead><tr><th>Method</th><th>What it does</th></tr></thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr><td><code>create_approval()</code></td><td>Opens an approval record tied to the pending mandate. Notifies via <code>ApprovalNotifier</code> (Slack / email / webhook).</td></tr>
            <tr><td><code>approve(approval_id, approver_id)</code></td><td>Marks approved; orchestrator resumes execution on next poll or event.</td></tr>
            <tr><td><code>deny(approval_id, reason)</code></td><td>Hard deny — decision log captures the human reason. The mandate is archived, not executable.</td></tr>
            <tr><td><code>cancel(approval_id)</code></td><td>Withdrawn by the agent (e.g. order was rescinded upstream).</td></tr>
            <tr><td><code>expire_pending()</code></td><td>Cron-called. Approvals have a TTL — stale requests don't execute days later when no one remembers.</td></tr>
            <tr><td><code>list_pending()</code></td><td>Powers the operator dashboard's approval inbox.</td></tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </section>

      <!-- Decision log -->
      <section class="section">
        <div class="section-header">
          <div class="eyebrow">Decision log</div>
          <h2>Every allow, every deny, one row.</h2>
          <p class="text-muted" style="max-width:760px;">
            The policy decision log is separate from the payment ledger — it captures policy outcomes
            whether or not a payment ever executed. A denied request still has to be evidenced: that's how
            the agent owner proves to a regulator that the system was working, not failing.
          </p>
        </div>
        <dl class="defs">
          <dt>Table</dt><dd><code>policy_decisions</code> (see canvas 05 · Database).</dd>
          <dt>Rows written when</dt><dd>Every call into <code>SpendingPolicy.evaluate()</code>, plus every approval transition.</dd>
          <dt>Fields</dt><dd>agent_id, mandate_id, reason_code, amount, merchant, chain, token, decided_at, approver_id (if any), evidence_hash.</dd>
          <dt>Anchoring</dt><dd>Batched into Merkle roots by <code>sardis-ledger</code>, anchored via <code>SardisLedgerAnchor.sol</code>.</dd>
          <dt>Export</dt><dd><code>evidence_export</code> router produces signed, proof-bearing CSV/JSON for audits.</dd>
        </dl>
      </section>

      <!-- Simulation -->
      <section class="section">
        <div class="section-header">
          <div class="eyebrow">Simulation</div>
          <h2>Test a policy before it enforces anything.</h2>
          <p class="text-muted" style="max-width:760px;">
            Policy changes are risky: tighten too much, block legitimate spending; loosen too much, invite
            incidents. The <code>policy_simulation</code> router
            (<code>packages/server-api/src/sardis/routers/policy_simulation.py</code>) replays historical
            traffic against a proposed policy and returns what would have changed — allows that became denies,
            denies that became allows, new approval routes.
          </p>
        </div>
        <div class="grid grid-2">
          <div class="card">
            <div class="card-title">Replay</div>
            <div class="card-description">
              Takes a time range of real mandates, runs them through the draft policy without touching
              wallets or chains. Output: diff of outcomes, broken down by reason code.
            </div>
          </div>
          <div class="card">
            <div class="card-title">What-if</div>
            <div class="card-description">
              Operator uploads a synthetic batch ("ten $150 API spends, two $2K one-offs"). Engine returns
              the full evaluation trail — same twelve checks, no side effects.
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </section>

      <!-- Kill switch -->
      <section class="section">
        <div class="section-header">
          <div class="eyebrow">Incident response</div>
          <h2>Kill switch — the big red button.</h2>
          <p class="text-muted" style="max-width:760px;">
            When something is clearly wrong ("every agent is suddenly trying to pay the same new address"),
            the operator needs one action that stops everything. The emergency router is that action.
          </p>
        </div>
        <dl class="defs">
          <dt>Router</dt><dd><code>packages/server-api/src/sardis/routers/emergency.py</code></dd>
          <dt>Dependency</dt><dd><code>packages/server-api/src/sardis/kill_switch_dep.py</code> — enforced on every write path.</dd>
          <dt>Effect</dt><dd>Global flag flips; <code>SpendingPolicy.evaluate()</code> short-circuits to deny with reason <code>kill_switch_active</code>; no new mandates accept; in-flight signatures are aborted at the wallet manager.</dd>
          <dt>Scope modes</dt><dd>Global, per-tenant, per-agent, per-chain — you don't always want to freeze everyone.</dd>
          <dt>Audit</dt><dd>Activation, reason, operator identity, and deactivation all log to the decision stream.</dd>
          <dt>Recovery</dt><dd>Manual — intentionally. Restoring spending after a kill requires explicit operator action, not a timeout.</dd>
        </dl>
      </section>

